  {
    "Section": {
      "level": 2,
      "title": "6. Canonicalization byte-injectivity (string-processing layer)",
      "doc": []
    }
  },
  {
    "Section": {
      "level": 2,
      "title": "method '\\n' body '\\n' canonHeaders '\\n' path '\\n' canonQuery",
      "doc": [
        "`canonicalizePayload` in cpp/src/canonical.cpp and rust/src/lib.rs produces",
        "the byte string the HMAC is computed over. The protocol's security goal —",
        "distinct requests yield distinct HMAC inputs — requires this canonical byte",
        "stream to be *injective* in the request. A failure here is exactly the",
        "shape of real-world signature-confusion vulnerabilities (AWS SigV4",
        "ambiguity, HTTP request smuggling).",
        "HISTORY. The original SDEP encoder concatenated variable-length fields",
        "with a single '\\n' delimiter:"
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "TypeAlias": {
      "name": "FL",
      "width": "16",
      "doc": [
        "method '\\n' body '\\n' canonHeaders '\\n' path '\\n' canonQuery",
        "That encoding is NOT injective: a newline smuggled into the body shifts",
        "the parse boundary into the next field, producing identical canonical",
        "bytes for distinct requests. (This was P23_CanonConcatInjective in earlier",
        "revisions of this file; Z3 exhibits a concrete two-field counterexample",
        "at every field length >= 2.)",
        "FIX. The encoder now prepends each variable-length field with its byte",
        "length (a fixed-width unsigned length tag). A parser reads exactly the",
        "declared number of bytes for each field, so no byte inside any field can",
        "be mistaken for a boundary. P23 below proves injectivity of this encoder.",
        "SCOPE OF THIS PROOF (bounded model checking).",
        "Cryptol + Z3 bit-blasts a fixed-size formula and hands it to SAT; there is",
        "no loop induction. The proof is over two fields of up to FL = 16 bytes",
        "each. It covers every concrete configuration at that size; the structural",
        "argument (a fixed-width length tag uniquely determines field boundaries)",
        "extends to arbitrary n and is what the production C++ / Rust encoders",
        "implement with a 64-bit big-endian length tag. A native-induction prover",
        "(Dafny / F* / Lean / Coq) or a SAW Hoare-logic proof over the loop in",
        "canonicalizePayload would extend the bound to all n.",
        "Field length in bytes (parameter for the bounded model)."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "TypeAlias": {
      "name": "IW",
      "width": "8",
      "doc": [
        "Index/length width: one byte is more than enough for FL <= 127."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "Function": {
      "name": "canonNormalized",
      "signature": "[IW] -> [FL][8] -> Bit",
      "branches": [
        {
          "condition": null,
          "result": "canonNormalized n b =\n    and [ (i >= n) ==> ((b @ i) == 0)\n        | i <- ([0 .. FL - 1] : [FL][IW]) ]"
        }
      ],
      "body": "canonNormalized n b =\n    and [ (i >= n) ==> ((b @ i) == 0)\n        | i <- ([0 .. FL - 1] : [FL][IW]) ]",
      "doc": [
        "A field is normalized iff bytes at indices >= n are zero. This is the",
        "invariant the C++ / Rust code maintains implicitly (it only reads the",
        "first n bytes); making it explicit keeps logically-distinct requests",
        "distinct as Cryptol values, so any collision the solver finds is a *real*",
        "one."
      ],
      "proof_status": null
    }
  },
  {
    "Function": {
      "name": "canonLenPrefixed",
      "signature": "[IW] -> [FL][8] -> [IW] -> [FL][8] -> [2 * FL + 2][8]",
      "branches": [
        {
          "condition": null,
          "result": "canonLenPrefixed nm m nb b = [nm] # m # [nb] # b"
        }
      ],
      "body": "canonLenPrefixed nm m nb b = [nm] # m # [nb] # b",
      "doc": [
        "Length-prefixed canonicalization. Each variable-length field is preceded",
        "by its length tag: a parser reads the tag, then exactly that many bytes,",
        "then the next tag, then exactly that many bytes. No byte inside any field",
        "can be misread as a boundary, so the encoding is structurally injective.",
        "The Cryptol bound uses an 8-bit length tag (sufficient for FL <= 255);",
        "production uses a 64-bit big-endian tag (sufficient for any std::size_t /",
        "usize field). The injectivity argument is identical for both widths."
      ],
      "proof_status": null
    }
  },
  {
    "Property": {
      "label": "P23",
      "name": "CanonicalizationInjective",
      "params": [
        "nm1",
        "m1",
        "nb1",
        "b1",
        "nm2",
        "m2",
        "nb2",
        "b2"
      ],
      "body": "( (nm1 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\\ (nb1 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\\\n(nm2 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\\ (nb2 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\\\ncanonNormalized nm1 m1 /\\ canonNormalized nb1 b1 /\\\ncanonNormalized nm2 m2 /\\ canonNormalized nb2 b2 /\\\ncanonLenPrefixed nm1 m1 nb1 b1 == canonLenPrefixed nm2 m2 nb2 b2 )\n==> ((nm1, m1, nb1, b1) == (nm2, m2, nb2, b2))",
      "doc": [
        "P23: Length-prefixed canonicalization is byte-injective — distinct",
        "normalized requests produce distinct canonical byte streams.",
        "EXPECTED VERDICT: PASS. This is the safety property the production",
        "canonicalizer satisfies after the delimiter -> length-prefix fix."
      ],
      "proof_status": null
    }
  },
  {
    "Section": {
      "level": 2,
      "title": "6.b Sub-canonicalizer injectivity — Tier-1 follow-up to P23.",
      "doc": []
    }
  },
  {
    "Property": {
      "label": "P24",
      "name": "HeaderCanonInjective",
      "params": [
        "nm1",
        "m1",
        "nb1",
        "b1",
        "nm2",
        "m2",
        "nb2",
        "b2"
      ],
      "body": "( (nm1 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\\ (nb1 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\\\n(nm2 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\\ (nb2 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\\\ncanonNormalized nm1 m1 /\\ canonNormalized nb1 b1 /\\\ncanonNormalized nm2 m2 /\\ canonNormalized nb2 b2 /\\\ncanonLenPrefixed nm1 m1 nb1 b1 == canonLenPrefixed nm2 m2 nb2 b2 )\n==> ((nm1, m1, nb1, b1) == (nm2, m2, nb2, b2))",
      "doc": [
        "The P23 fix length-prefixes the FIVE TOP-LEVEL fields of the canonical",
        "payload (method | body | canonHeaders | path | canonQuery). The inner",
        "canonicalizers `canonicalize_headers` and `canonicalize_query` now use",
        "the SAME length-prefix scheme for every individual name and value they",
        "emit (an 8-byte big-endian length tag followed by the raw bytes), so",
        "they are structurally byte-injective in their input map by the same",
        "argument that proves P23: a parser reads <tag, name, tag, value> in",
        "fixed order with no byte inside any name or value capable of being",
        "misread as a record boundary.",
        "Historical note: an earlier revision joined records with '\\n' (headers)",
        "or '&' (query) and fields inside each record with ':' / '='. That",
        "encoding admitted a header / query smuggling collision (a value",
        "containing \"\\nname:forged\" parsed as an extra record under a forged",
        "header name). Concrete production-code collisions for that earlier",
        "encoding were exhibited in rust/tests/validate_canon_gaps.rs.",
        "P24: `canonicalize_headers` is byte-injective in the header map.",
        "The production encoder length-prefixes every name and value with an",
        "8-byte big-endian tag (same shape as canonicalizePayload), so distinct",
        "normalized header records produce distinct canonical byte streams.",
        "EXPECTED VERDICT: PASS — the encoding closes the smuggling gap."
      ],
      "proof_status": null
    }
  },
  {
    "Property": {
      "label": "P25",
      "name": "QueryCanonInjective",
      "params": [
        "nm1",
        "m1",
        "nb1",
        "b1",
        "nm2",
        "m2",
        "nb2",
        "b2"
      ],
      "body": "( (nm1 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\\ (nb1 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\\\n(nm2 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\\ (nb2 <= (`FL : [IW])) /\\\ncanonNormalized nm1 m1 /\\ canonNormalized nb1 b1 /\\\ncanonNormalized nm2 m2 /\\ canonNormalized nb2 b2 /\\\ncanonLenPrefixed nm1 m1 nb1 b1 == canonLenPrefixed nm2 m2 nb2 b2 )\n==> ((nm1, m1, nb1, b1) == (nm2, m2, nb2, b2))",
      "doc": [
        "P25: `canonicalize_query` is byte-injective in the query map.",
        "Same length-prefix shape; no separators are needed because the length",
        "tag uniquely marks each record boundary.",
        "EXPECTED VERDICT: PASS."
      ],
      "proof_status": null
    }
  },
  {
    "Section": {
      "level": 2,
      "title": "6.c enforceAccess matrix-coverage gap — Tier-3 follow-up.",
      "doc": []
    }
  },
  {
    "Property": {
      "label": "P26",
      "name": "EnforceNoRuleAllowsSilently",
      "params": [],
      "body": "enforceAccess AM_Enforce AD_NoRule == (True, False)",
      "doc": [
        "P11..P14 cover only 5 of the 9 cells of the (AccessMode × AccessDecision)",
        "matrix, and P12 only checks the `.0 = allowed` projection (not the",
        "`.1 = logged` flag). The two properties below close the matrix.",
        "EXPECTED VERDICT: PASS — they document previously-unverified behaviour",
        "of the existing model.",
        "P26: Enforce mode with no matching rule allows silently (matches the",
        "spec's implicit fall-through and the C++/Rust impl's `else` branch)."
      ],
      "proof_status": null
    }
  },
  {
    "Property": {
      "label": "P27",
      "name": "AuditLoggedOnlyOnDeny",
      "params": [
        "decision"
      ],
      "body": "isAccessDecision decision ==>\n(enforceAccess AM_Audit decision).1 == (decision == AD_Deny)",
      "doc": [
        "P27: Audit mode logs IFF the underlying decision is Deny — never on",
        "Allow or NoRule. Closes the .1 = logged projection that P12 leaves",
        "unspecified."
      ],
      "proof_status": null
    }
  },
  {
    "Section": {
      "level": 2,
      "title": "6.d Tier-2 gaps and what blocks them.",
      "doc": []
    }
  },
  {
    "Section": {
      "level": 2,
      "title": "7. Compositional refinement — structured Request model",
      "doc": [
        "The following three properties are real and would meaningfully strengthen",
        "the spec, but each is blocked by a distinct obstacle:",
        "(Gap 4)  AUTH-HEADER EXCLUSION",
        "canonicalizePayload must be independent of the",
        "x-fleet-authorization header value.",
        "BLOCKED BY: the `Request = [256]` abstraction. The whole point",
        "of collapsing the canonical bytes into one opaque Cryptol",
        "value was to keep P8/P9 cheap; that collapse erases the",
        "internal structure (headers, etc.) needed to *state* this",
        "property.  STATEMENT (after refactor):",
        "property P_AuthExcluded r v1 v2 =",
        "canonicalize (r withAuth v1) == canonicalize (r withAuth v2)",
        "COST: replace abstract Request with a structured record type",
        "{ method, path, headers : [N](Name, Value), body, timestamp }",
        "and rebuild isValidSignature on top of it. One refactor also",
        "unblocks Gap 6.",
        "(Gap 6)  TIMESTAMP BINDING — FIXED.",
        "The timestamp validated by isValidRequestDate is now bound",
        "into the signed canonical bytes: `DeviceRequest::timestamp`",
        "is appended to canonicalizePayload, and `handle_activate`",
        "passes `request.timestamp` (NOT a caller parameter) to",
        "`isValidRequestDate`. Mechanised as P29_TimestampBound",
        "against the structured `RequestS` model; the historical",
        "`requestTimestampUnix` caller parameter has been removed.",
        "(Gap 5)  CONSTANT-TIME COMPARISON",
        "constant_time_equals must execute the same sequence of basic",
        "blocks regardless of which byte position first differs.",
        "BLOCKED BY: Cryptol's semantic universe. Cryptol is a pure",
        "functional spec language — it describes *values*, not",
        "*executions*. The constant-time and variable-time",
        "implementations of byte-equality are *the same Cryptol",
        "function* (`\\a b -> a == b`), so no Cryptol property can tell",
        "them apart. This obligation belongs at the SAW / LLVM level:",
        "symbolic execution of `crypto::constant_time_equals` for",
        "inputs that differ only in *where* they first diverge must",
        "produce the same control-flow trace. SAW can express this via",
        "`crucible_path_condition`-style assertions; it just isn't",
        "wired up here yet."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "TypeAlias": {
      "name": "FLs",
      "width": "2     // field length bound, bytes",
      "doc": [
        "The opaque `Request = [256]` is sufficient for HMAC algebra (P8, P9) but",
        "blocks any property that needs to look INSIDE the request. We add a",
        "STRUCTURED layer alongside the abstract one. Existing properties P1–P27",
        "keep reasoning about `Request = [256]`; new properties P28+ reason about",
        "`RequestS`. The two layers are linked by viewing the abstract `Request`",
        "as some hash of `canonicalizeS r`; that bridge is documentary — no",
        "property below depends on it, so the refinement is purely additive.",
        "Bounded sizes for BMC: 2-byte fields, 2 headers per request. This is",
        "small enough to keep Z3 fast (~1s/property) and large enough to exhibit",
        "every structural counterexample shape we care about."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "TypeAlias": {
      "name": "Ns",
      "width": "2     // bounded header count",
      "doc": []
    }
  },
  {
    "RecordType": {
      "name": "Field",
      "fields": [
